{King and pawn endgames are the foundation of all endgame play. Understanding opposition and key squares is essential.} 1. Kf4 {White advances the king in front of the pawn — this is the critical technique.} (1. e5? {A common beginner mistake — pushing the pawn too early.} Ke7 {Black takes the opposition.} 2. Ke4 Ke6 {Black has the opposition and draws.} 3. Kd4 Kd7 4. Kd5 Ke7 5. e6 Ke8 6. Kd6 Kd8 7. e7+ Ke8 8. Ke6 {Stalemate! The pawn push was premature.}) Kd6 {Black tries to stay in front of the pawn.} (1... Kf6 {Keeping the opposition.} 2. e5+ Ke6 3. Ke4 {White regains the opposition.} Kd7 (3... Ke7 4. Kd5 Kd7 5. e6+ Ke7 6. Ke5 Ke8 7. Kd6 Kd8 8. e7+ Ke8 9. Ke6 {Stalemate again! This shows how tricky these positions are.}) 4. Kf5 Ke7 5. e6 {Now it works because White has the opposition.} Ke8 6. Kf6 Kd8 (6... Kf8 7. e7+ Ke8 8. Ke6 {Stalemate — always be careful not to push too eagerly.}) 7. e7+ Kd7 {Forced.} 8. Kf7 {The king controls the queening square.} Kd6 9. e8=Q {White queens and wins.}) 2. Kf5 Ke7 3. Ke5 {White has the opposition — the key concept. The defending king must give way.} Kd7 4. Kf6 Ke8 5. e5 Kd7 (5. -- Kf8 6. e6 Ke8 7. e7 Kd7 8. Kf7 {The king escorts the pawn to promotion.} Kd6 9. e8=Q) 6. Kf7 {The king controls the queening square.} Kd8 7. e6 Kc7 {The only move — Kc8 also loses.} (7... Kc8 8. e7 Kd7 9. e8=Q+ {White promotes and wins.}) 8. e7 Kd6 9. e8=Q {White promotes and wins. The principle: advance the king first, push the pawn second.} *
